{
 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "from mpl_toolkits.mplot3d import Axes3D\n",
    "from matplotlib import cm\n",
    "plt.style.use('bmh')\n",
    "\n",
    "# custom figure styles\n",
    "from plot_style import std_fig"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Classification and logistic regression"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Classification problems\n",
    "__Classification problems__ are like regression problems, but the predicted values $y$ of our model $h$ now take on discrete values. This section will focus on the __binary classfication__ problem, in which $y$ takes values only in $\\{0, 1\\}$. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Logistic regression\n",
    "### The logistic function"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Logistic regression is horribly named, because it doesn't do regression at all; it is a method of doing classification."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "g = lambda z: 1/(1 + np.exp(-z))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We start by defining the __logistic function__ or __sigmoid\n",
    "function__.\n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{equation}\n",
    "g(z) = \\frac{1}{1+e^{-z}} \n",
    "\\end{equation}"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 288x288 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "z = np.linspace(-7, 7, 100)\n",
    "with std_fig() as (fig, ax):\n",
    "    ax.plot(z, g(z))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The logistic function $g(z)$ tends to 0 as $z\\to -\\infty$ and tends to 1 as\n",
    "$z\\to +\\infty$. But the important point is that $g(z)$ is always bounded between\n",
    "0 and 1 (other functions that are smooth and increase from 0 to 1 could\n",
    "also work, but it turns out the logistic function is a natural choice; see notes\n",
    "on generalized linear models for more information). __The important point is that the logistic function can map a function defined on the reals to a probability.__\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "The logistic function has the useful property that \n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{equation}\n",
    "g^\\prime(z) = \\frac{d }{d z} \\frac{1}{1+e^{-z}} = g(z) \\left(1-g(z)\\right)\n",
    "\\end{equation}"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### The logistic regression hypothesis"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Our modified hypothesis $h_\\theta(x)$ is \n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{equation}\n",
    "h_\\theta(x) = g\\left(\\theta^T x\\right) = \\frac{1}{1+e^{-\\theta^T x}},\n",
    "\\end{equation}\n",
    "\n",
    "A good way to understand logistic regression (similar to the probabilistic\n",
    "interpretation of linear regression) is to endow the classification model with a\n",
    "set of probabilistic properties and then fit the parameters in a maximum\n",
    "likelihood sense."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Interpretation of hypothesis output and decision boundary"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Note that for data $x$ and a given $\\theta$, the hypothesis $h_\\theta(x)$\n",
    "returns a scalar. However, the hypothesis function $h_\\theta(x)$ is a continuous function of $x$, so it seems that we are no closer to our goal of a classification algorithm,\n",
    "which should ultimately return a decision whether a new point should be\n",
    "classified as 0 or 1.\n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{align}\n",
    "P(y=1|x;\\theta) &= h_\\theta(x) \\\\\n",
    "P(y=0|x;\\theta) &= 1-h_\\theta(x)\n",
    "\\end{align}\n",
    "\n",
    "The random variable $Y|X;\\theta$ is distributed as a Bernoulli random variable.\n",
    "\n",
    "By interpreting the outputs as a Bernoulli random variable, we have a natural\n",
    "way of making the decision. We can classify a new data point $x_{new}$ as \n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{align}\n",
    "y=1 \\qquad &\\text{if} \\qquad h_\\theta(x_{new}) \\geq 0.5 \\\\\n",
    "y=0 \\qquad &\\text{if} \\qquad h_\\theta(x_{new}) < 0.5 \\\\\n",
    "\\end{align}\n",
    "\n",
    "Considering the behavior of the logistic function $g(z)$, we have that \n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{align}\n",
    "g(z) \\geq 0.5 \\qquad &\\text{if} \\qquad \\theta^T x_{new} \\geq 0 \\\\\n",
    "g(z) < 0.5 \\qquad &\\text{if} \\qquad \\theta^T x_{new} < 0\n",
    "\\end{align}\n",
    "\n",
    "which implies that the hyperplane $\\theta^T x=0$ is separating the space. We refer\n",
    "to the hyperplane as the __decision boundary__. There are generalizations of this to nonlinear separating boundaries; we defer discussion of this generalization for the time being."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Example: actuarial prediction \n",
    "\n",
    "As an illustrative example, suppose we have a simple actuarial model which\n",
    "attempts to predict the probability of being dead in the next month given a\n",
    "person's age and cholesterol. All of these numbers are cooked up.\n",
    "\n",
    "We suppose that $\\theta = [-210, 2.3, 0.5]$ has already been computed from training data. Our feature vector is $x = (x_0,\\, x_1,\\, x_2)$ where $x_0 =1$ is the offset (hence 1 by\n",
    "convention), $x_1$ is age in years, and $x_2$ is LDL cholesterol level in mmol/L. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "age = np.linspace(0, 100, 50)\n",
    "ldl_cholesterol = np.linspace(50, 200, 50)\n",
    "AGE, LDL = np.meshgrid(age, ldl_cholesterol)\n",
    "θ = [2.3, 0.5]\n",
    "offset = -210"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "For all possible ages and cholesteral levels $x$, $\\theta^T x$ can be thought of\n",
    "as a plane, and the sigmoid function maps the plane (which is not bounded), to\n",
    "the probability of death given the input point $(x_1,\\, x_2)$."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "plane = offset + θ[0]*AGE + θ[1]*LDL\n",
    "P_death = g(plane)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 720x288 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "fig = plt.figure(figsize=plt.figaspect(0.4))\n",
    "ax = fig.add_subplot(1, 2, 1, projection='3d')\n",
    "surf = ax.plot_wireframe(AGE, LDL, plane, rstride=10, cstride=5)\n",
    "ax.set_title(r'$\\theta^T x$', y=0.95); ax.set_xlabel('age');\n",
    "ax.dist= 12\n",
    "\n",
    "ax = fig.add_subplot(1, 2, 2, projection='3d')\n",
    "surf = ax.plot_wireframe(AGE, LDL, P_death, rstride=10, cstride=5,)\n",
    "ax.set_title(r'$g(\\theta^T x)$', y=0.95); ax.set_xlabel('age');\n",
    "ax.dist= 12"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The graphs and weights lend themselves to an intuitive interpretation. From $g\\left(\\theta^T\n",
    "x\\right)$, we see that even with very low cholesterol, probability of death\n",
    "increases dramatically past age 65. We also see from $\\theta$ that age has\n",
    "more of an effect on probability of death than cholesterol: even with very bad\n",
    "cholesterol, a 40 year old is almost certainly not going to die within the next \n",
    "month, in our model. However, a doctor might recommend that he or she strive for\n",
    "lower LDL levels, since the model predicts death at 60 rather than 80 with bad\n",
    "cholesterol."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### How to train the hypothesis on data"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "However, we can do a trick where we write the Bernoulli random variable as a continuous random variable in\n",
    "an equivalent way\n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{equation}\n",
    "p(y|x;\\theta) = \\left(h_\\theta(x)\\right)^y \\left(1-h_\\theta(x)\\right)^{1-y}\n",
    "\\end{equation}"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "h = lambda θ, x: 1./(1 + np.exp(-np.dot(θ, x)))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Let's take a 1D example with $\\theta=1$ and $x=1$\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 8,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "0.7310585786300049"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 8,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "θ = 1; x = 1\n",
    "h(θ, x)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 288x288 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "y = np.linspace(-0.1, 1.1, 50)\n",
    "r = h(θ,x)**y * (1-h(θ, x))**(1-y)\n",
    "with std_fig() as (fig, ax):\n",
    "    ax.plot(y, r, zorder=0, label=r'$p(y|x;\\theta)$')\n",
    "    ax.scatter([0, 1], [1-h(θ,x), h(θ,x)], c='k', s=80)\n",
    "    ax.legend(prop={'size': 16})"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "And we see that the continuous function matches the discrete PMF at the points $\\{0,1\\}$ so if we restrict the domain of $y$ to this set, we have agreement. We could see this also by choosing $y$ to be 0 or 1 and evaluating directly.\n",
    "\n",
    "At first, it seems like we're taking a step backward, because we've gone from a\n",
    "discrete decision back to a continuous representation, but the approach will be\n",
    "similar to the probabilistic interpretation of linear regression. **We will find\n",
    "an expression for the likelihood and then maximize it to find the most likely\n",
    "explanation for the observations given the data.**"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Since all of the training examples were generated independently, we can write\n",
    "the likelihood as \n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{align}\n",
    "L(\\theta) &= p(y|X;\\theta) \\\\\n",
    "&= \\prod_{i=1}^m p\\left(y^{(i)}|x^{(i)};\\theta\\right) \\\\\n",
    "&= \\prod_{i=1}^m \\left[h_\\theta\\left(x^{(i)}\\right)\\right]^{y^{(i)}} \\left[1-h_\\theta\\left(x^{(i)}\\right)\\right]^{1-y^{(i)}}\n",
    "\\end{align}\n",
    "\n",
    "We once again (just as in the probabilistic interpretation of of linear\n",
    "regression) maximize the log likelihood\n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{align}\n",
    "\\ell(\\theta) &= \\log\n",
    "\\prod_{i=1}^m \\left[h_\\theta\\left(x^{(i)}\\right)\\right]^{y^{(i)}}\n",
    "\\left[1-h_\\theta\\left(x^{(i)}\\right)\\right]^{1-y^{(i)}} \\\\\n",
    "&= \\sum_{i=1}^{m}\\left(y^{(i)} \\log h_\\theta\\left(x^{(i)}\\right) +\n",
    "\\left(1-y^{(i)}\\right) \\log\\left(1-h_\\theta(x^{(i)})\\right)\\right)\n",
    "\\end{align}"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "If we want to use a gradient ascent algorithm, we need to evaluate the update\n",
    "rule\n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{equation}\n",
    "\\theta_j := \\theta_j + \\alpha \\frac{\\partial }{\\partial \\theta_j} \\ell(\\theta)\n",
    "\\end{equation}\n",
    "\n",
    "which follows in the direction of the gradient rather than against it since we\n",
    "are trying to maximize $\\ell(\\theta)$. We consider the derivative for the case\n",
    "of a single training example $x$ and $y$. The more general case can be written\n",
    "by including the sum and adding the superscripts.\n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{align}\n",
    "\\frac{\\partial }{\\partial \\theta_j}\\ell(\\theta) \n",
    "&= \\frac{\\partial }{\\partial \\theta_j}\n",
    "\\left(y \\log g(\\theta^T x)  +\n",
    "\\left(1-y\\right) \\log\\left(1- g(\\theta^T x)\\right)\\right) \\\\\n",
    "&= \\left(y \\frac{1}{g(\\theta^T x)} \n",
    "\\frac{\\partial }{\\partial\n",
    "\\theta_j}g(\\theta^T x)\n",
    "+ (1-y)\\frac{1}{1-g(\\theta^T x)}\n",
    "\\frac{\\partial }{\\partial \\theta_j}\\left(1-g(\\theta^T x)\\right)\n",
    "\\right) \\\\\n",
    "&= \\left(y \\frac{1}{g(\\theta^T x)} \n",
    "- (1-y)\\frac{1}{1-g(\\theta^T x)}\n",
    "\\right)\n",
    "\\frac{\\partial }{\\partial \\theta_j}g(\\theta^T x) \\\\\n",
    "&= \\left(y \\frac{1}{g(\\theta^T x)} - (1-y)\\frac{1}{1-g(\\theta^T x)} \\right)\n",
    "g(\\theta^T x) \\left(1- g(\\theta^T x) \\right)\n",
    "\\frac{\\partial }{\\partial \\theta_j}\\left(\\theta^T x\\right) \\\\\n",
    "&= \\left(y\\left(1-g(\\theta^T x)\\right)  - (1-y) g(\\theta^T x) \\right) x_j \\\\\n",
    "&= \\left(y - h_{\\theta}(x)\\right)x_j\n",
    "\\end{align}"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "So the update rule in all of its glory (with the training set indices, etc) is \n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{equation}\n",
    "\\theta_j := \\theta_j + \\alpha\\left( y^{(i)} -\n",
    "h_\\theta\\left(x^{(i)}\\right)\\right),\n",
    "\\end{equation}\n",
    "\n",
    "It's worth pointing out that any constants involved in the sum can be rolled\n",
    "into the learning rate $\\alpha$ since it's a parameter that has to be tuned\n",
    "anyway.  The update rule looks the same as the least mean squares update, but\n",
    "this is only cosmetic. The function $h_\\theta(x)$ is now the nonlinear logistic\n",
    "function."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Locally weighted logistic regression"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,

   ]
  }
